**DO NOT MERGE UNTIL WE CUT AN HDK RELEASE WITHOUT THIS**


# summary

ultimately makes this code work:

```rust
use hdk::prelude::*;

#[hdk_entry(id = "something")]
#[derive(Clone)]
struct Something(#[serde(with = "serde_bytes")] Vec<u8>);

#[hdk_entry(id = "entry_reference")]
struct EntryReference(EntryHash);

impl EntryReference {
    fn into_inner(self) -> EntryHash {
        self.0
    }
}

#[hdk_entry(id = "header_reference")]
struct HeaderReference(HeaderHash);

impl HeaderReference {
    fn into_inner(self) -> HeaderHash {
        self.0
    }
}

#[hdk_entry(id = "element_reference")]
struct ElementReference(HeaderHash);

impl ElementReference {
    fn into_inner(self) -> HeaderHash {
        self.0
    }
}

#[hdk_extern]
fn validate_create_entry_entry_reference(data: ValidateData) -> ExternResult<ValidateCallbackResult> {
    let entry_reference = EntryReference::try_from(&data.element)?;

    let entry_hashed: EntryHashed = must_get_entry(entry_reference.into_inner())?;
    let entry: Entry = entry_hashed.clone().into();
    let _something_hashed: Something = entry_hashed.try_into()?;
    let _something: Something = entry.try_into()?;

    Ok(ValidateCallbackResult::Valid)
}

#[hdk_extern]
fn validate_create_entry_header_reference(data: ValidateData) -> ExternResult<ValidateCallbackResult> {
    let header_reference = HeaderReference::try_from(&data.element)?;

    let signed_header_hashed: SignedHeaderHashed = must_get_header(header_reference.into_inner())?;
    let _header: Header = signed_header_hashed.into();

    Ok(ValidateCallbackResult::Valid)
}

#[hdk_extern]
fn validate_create_entry_element_reference(data: ValidateData) -> ExternResult<ValidateCallbackResult> {
    let element_reference = ElementReference::try_from(&data.element)?;

    let element: Element = must_get_valid_element(element_reference.into_inner())?;
    let _something: Something = element.try_into()?;

    Ok(ValidateCallbackResult::Valid)
}
```

Note use of new deterministic network functions `must_get_entry`, `must_get_header` and `must_get_valid_element`.

Network functions are deterministic because the non-deterministic behaviour short circuits callbacks on the host, and returns `WasmError` for regular zome functions. This means significantly fewer foot guns in validation logic, and also removes the largest source of mocks in happ unit testing (network failures). The guest does not need to have an opinion on network failures or missing dependencies, the host should know what to do with any such failures.

Also note liberal use of `try_into()` and `?` between element, entries and application data, as well as `ExternResult`.

Currently this is not possible and/or safe because either the impls didn't exist or `?` would send e.g. deserialization failures to `Err(WasmError)` instead of `Ok(ValidateCallbackResult::Invalid)`. Now the host knows to treat serializaton and guest wasm errors as invalid/fail variants of callbacks.

__it also disables non-deterministic network access during validation callbacks__

# changes

- holochain wasmer to v0.0.70
- fully qualified namespaces in fixt macros
- allow setting index in `fixt!`
- added `must_get_entry` and `must_get_header` and `must_get_valid_element`
- removed fail case on entry defs callback which should be handled as an actual error
- renamed `HostAccess` to `HostContext` now that we're using it for more than just access
- added `try_from_wasm_error` to `CallbackResult` trait and host uses it to try to map errors to results for callbacks
- `call_test_ribosome!` returns a result now instead of panicking all failures, so we can test more failure modes
- `GenesisSelfCheckResult` maps to `ValidateCallbackResult` on the host now
- Init supports `AnyDhtHash` for `UnresolvedDependencies` so it can support all `must_get_x`
- access checks are split into `foo` and `foo_deterministic` sections
- minor refactor in the cascade
- various impls for app entry types from element/entry data
- disable access to non-determinism where it is dangerous
